    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>129100</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Πτολεμαῖος"><unclear>Π</unclear>τολεμαῖος</name> 
                        <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Π_" type="patronymic"><seg part="I"><unclear>Π</unclear></seg><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name></persName></persName>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Ptolémaios fils de P<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Ptolemaios son of P<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Ptolemaios figlio di P<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>Too many names might be restored as the father's name. The name of the kings of Egypt (including for some periods Cyrenaica) was 
               very popular in Hellenistic times for people of all social levels. However, in the lower layers, it was progressively changed into 
               <foreign xml:lang="grc">Πτυλ(ε)μαῖος</foreign>. The use of the traditional form shows that its bearer was sticking at some degree to traditions.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
